Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
The Sunoco/Energy Transfer pipeline leak in Upper Makefield has raised serious concerns about public health, environmental safety, and regulatory oversight. While PADEP has responded to some inquiries, critical questions remain unanswered—questions that demand immediate and thorough responses.

As I continue working alongside the dedicated residents of the Upper Makefield Task Force and in addition to my calls for PHMSA to temporarily shut down the pipeline, I am once again calling on PADEP Acting Secretary Jessica Shirley to provide greater accountability, independent oversight, and a firm commitment to full environmental remediation.

Among the most pressing questions PADEP must answer:

✔️ Why is PADEP downplaying public concerns about MTBE, Lead, and VOCs? Any level of contamination—especially near a nearly 70-year-old petroleum pipeline—should be treated as a serious risk.

✔️ Why is Energy Transfer’s own contractor conducting the testing? Independent, third-party verification is essential to ensuring public trust and accurate results.

✔️ Why hasn’t PADEP required full environmental restoration? A pipeline leak of this magnitude demands more than minimal compliance—it requires a complete and thorough cleanup.

PADEP must act decisively to protect residents and hold Energy Transfer fully accountable. Our community deserves transparency and real solutions, not delays or half-measures. I will keep pushing until we get the accountability this situation demands.

Read my full letter here: ⬇️

Name: Stansbury, Melanie A.
text:
Per reporting, this is likely to happen tomorrow. ⬇️

Trump‘s efforts to dismantle the Department of Education is not only an affront to the millions of students served by the Department, but it violates the law. Put simply, the President and his Administration do not have the authority to shutter agencies created and funded by Congress. I am confident that the courts will find, just as they have in dozens of similar cases over the last several weeks, that Trump’s efforts to dismantle the agency violate congressional mandates and appropriations, federal employment laws, and the fundamental separation of powers enshrined in the U.S. Constitution. Over the last 45 years, the Department of Education has played a vital role in helping to make public education available to millions of public school kids across America, including myself. We will fight back every step of the way because our kids are depending on us!

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
My third visit to Mexico City and a lot has changed for the good. The time is now to take the fight to the cartels. What has changed?

President Trump has made this a priority just like he said he would.

President Sheinbaum and her head of security Omar Harfuch are breaking records in drug busts and arrests, targeting Sinaloa’s fentanyl production mostly. They are also open to American help for the first time in…maybe ever. 

This is a terrorist-insurgency problem that is destroying Mexico and killing Americans. Defeating the cartels will require a Counter-Insurgency strategy that involves every agency in both the U.S. and Mexico. 

Our biggest problem? Congress still isn’t focused. I’ve worked for over a year as head of our Cartel Task Force (with no additional staff and no funding) to develop a whole-of-government strategy to defeat the cartels and produce the legislation that President Trump will need. But there is more work to do. It’s why I asked @SpeakerJohnson to create a Select Committee on Cartels so we could hire proper staff and get the legislation right. He told me that he agreed. So do all the Chairmen that co-sponsored the select committee idea, like @Jim_Jordan, @JamesComer, @RepBrianMast, @RepMikeRogersAL, @RepMarkGreen, @RepFrenchHill, @RepGuthrie, @RepBrianBabin, @RepBryanSteil, and @RepMichaelGuest. 

It’s a no brainer. We should vote on it next week and get to work.

Name: Goodlander, Maggie
text:
Do you know someone who relies on Medicaid?

Across New Hampshire, more than 180,000 people rely on Medicaid to live their lives. One of those people is John Dery, who has multiple sclerosis. At a recent town hall in Keene, John and his wife Claudia stood up and shared the absolutely essential role Medicaid plays in their daily lives. I will never forget what they shared with me that day. 

Yesterday, I visited the Monadnock Adult Care Center in Jaffrey, where John is an essential member of that extraordinary community. Seeing firsthand the life-changing care that people from 16 towns across New Hampshire receive there every single day gives me hope and the energy I need for the fight to protect Medicaid.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: What’s actually happening is a pattern of very bad, even dangerous, courtroom conduct by Trump lawyers, I guess thinking that being MAGA entitles them to special rules and privileges — but not so. Here are examples.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Trumpsters pretend that the courts are out of line, even that judges should be impeached when they don’t like the rulings, but that’s hogwash. Even Chief Justice Roberts is calling out that crap, which is saying something.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Firing someone based on false allegations of poor performance creates very clear legal recourse, so expect that to be litigated, over and over, and lots of plain simple lying exposed. Lying by lawyers in court proceedings is sanctionable.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 2.  Trump lawyers tried to invent a fake criminal investigation in an effort to freeze a climate fund at a bank. Career DOJ attorneys refused, their chief was forced to resign, and then a judge shot down the freeze effort. So they went to another district to try again.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 1.  Trump lawyers were warned by in-house agency counsel — twice — that saying employees were fired for poor performance would be “fraud” on the court. Yet they went ahead and did it anyway. It was expedient.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: False claims of “fraud” and “criminality” uttered by Trump officials are defamatory per se, so expect that to be litigated, and plain simple lying exposed. A federal judge has granted a TRO protecting the fund, throwing out Trump lawyers’ unsupported arguments.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 3.  Trump lawyers may have misled multiple federal judges about deportations and then violated federal court orders on various pretexts and pretenses.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Judges are not amused by that, and you can expect them to do fact-finding and get to the bottom of whether there was deliberate contempt of court. Contempt of court is punishable by the court, and civil contempt is not pardonable.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 4.  In the original case holding the Trump spending freeze unconstitutional, Trump lawyers withdrew the OMB directive imposing the freeze, to “comply” with the order, but kept the actual freeze in place notwithstanding the court order.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Lawyers have a duty of candor to a tribunal, a duty of fair dealing to other parties in court, and an obligation to obey court orders. Just being a Trump lawyer doesn’t make any of that go away — and federal judges are and should be rigorous about enforcing honorable behavior.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: That’s a pretty cheap trick, and the judge saw right through it, so good luck going back in her courtroom with any credibility after pulling a stunt like that. Obviously the point of the proceeding was the freeze, not the directive.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Left untreated, bacterial infections can be deadly, and effective treatment is becoming more challenging as bacteria becomes resistant to our most potent anti-bacterial drugs. That's why I am thankful for the continued work of @VenatorxPharma, a Malvern-based pharmaceutical research company, creating new anti-infectives to treat drug-resistant bacterial infections. Venatorx relies heavily on financial support from the National Institutes of Health (NIH), which President Trump has repeatedly attacked. 

The Trump Administration has attempted to freeze NIH grants, reduce the cap on "indirect" research costs, and steeply cut the NIH's workforce. These moves won't just halt life-saving research; they are flat-out illegal. That is why I led a letter with my colleagues to the NIH director demanding a reversal of the unlawful change to the cap on indirect costs, and I am happy that a federal court has temporarily blocked the Trump Administration's harmful action, allowing vital biomedical research like that of Venatorx to continue.

Name: Doggett, Lloyd
text:
Today, Trump signed an Executive Order directing Secretary McMahon to take all necessary steps to dismantle the Department of Education, an agency that serves over 5.6 million students across 9,000 Texas K-12 schools. This reckless, unlawful action doesn’t just skirt Congressional authority—it endangers the support for the most vulnerable students and schools in Texas: the 700,000 students with disabilities, the $140 million allocated for bilingual learners, and the $1.8 billion in funding for Title I schools that serve over 3.6 million students, including many in Austin.

As a product of Austin public schools myself and as a father and grandfather of successful AISD students, I know the value dedicated educators bring to our community. Our public schools are vital for both individual opportunity and our continued economic promise.

It’s so appropriate that Governor Abbott has joined President Trump for this announcement, since both are undermining public education. Their attacks on federal support for education are furthered by their promotion of state and federal voucher schemes. This isn’t just about policy—it’s about priorities. Abbott’s and Trump’s actions cater to the demands of billionaire donors to redirect these funds to finance private academies and trillions in tax breaks.

President Trump may claim to put America first, but this latest move makes it painfully clear: he is putting us last. In Texas alone, the Department provides over $580 million to support our workforce. Yet Trump, out of touch with the lived experience of working families, seeks to cripple investment in both our students and our future workforce. His agenda, supported by Elon Musk and Governor Abbott, is simple: starve our public schools—the foundation of our democracy—of resources that create well-informed citizens. Why? So it’s easier to sell their backward beliefs, peddle their “alternative facts,” and secure a future where ignorance is a weapon.

Because the Department of Education was established by statute enacted by Congress, Trump has no authority to shut it down by Executive Order. This is another attempt to overwhelm and wear down the American people. The hundreds of messages I have received on this issue demonstrate that Austin, the only place I have ever called home, will never surrender. We stand together, fighting for every student’s right to succeed and against this illegal power grab.

Name: Lee, Susie
text:
I spent a lot of time working in public schools before I ran for Congress.

What I witnessed was some of our most disadvantaged students getting the help they need because of funding and protections from the U.S. Department of Education. That includes the nearly 70,000 Nevada students with disabilities who rely on federal funding for additional attention from aides, teachers, and special ed programs. Or the roughly 67 percent of students in Clark County who are eligible for additional resources in terms of free and reduced lunch and other programs.

Our classrooms are already overcrowded because we don’t have enough educators, and with this move teachers and aides will be laid off making our classrooms even more crowded.

Despite the fact that only Congress can shutter the Department of Education, this move is about taking money from our most at-risk students so Trump can reward his wealthy friends with tax breaks. It’s disgusting.

I’ve spent my career fighting for kids and we will fight this illegal action.

Name: Hassan, Margaret Wood
text:
The President’s decision today to dismantle the Department of Education will hurt our children and leave them less prepared for the future, just at a time when America should be working across party lines to strengthen our schools, families, and teachers. 
 
All across the Granite State there are vibrant public schools that provide critical public education to students from all walks of life. They do so with the essential help of the federal Department of Education, which provides funding and technical expertise to schools so that they can support children who need extra support in the classroom — children whose families are struggling financially, children who are facing mental health challenges, and children with disabilities. The challenges that these children and their families face won’t go away because President Trump and Elon Musk turn their backs on them. Instead, the decision to shutter the Department of Education will leave some children in our country without the education that they deserve and shift costs to local communities, raising property taxes. 
 
Our education system is challenged, to be sure, but rather than focus on how to help our local school districts provide the best possible education for all of our children, the Administration has run away from the opportunity and obligation to ensure that all American children can receive a quality education to prepare them for adulthood. Once again, Trump and Musk shrink from the responsibilities and promise of our democracy.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
This is wonderful news for Alaska. Secretary Burgum recognizes Alaska’s incredible resource potential and the increasingly onerous restrictions that have been put in place—over our objections—to stop us from responsibly producing and reaching our full potential as a state. He recognizes our petroleum reserve as a petroleum reserve, the Coastal Plain as our nation’s most prospective source for conventional oil and gas, and the need to move forward on both the Ambler Road and AKLNG. These are the first steps to restoring reasonable access to our federal lands and the federal government fulfilling the terms of our statehood compact from nearly 70 years ago—all achieved by simply partnering with Alaskans and following the law. Name: Sullivan, Dan
text: .@SecretaryBurgum’s announcement today—which implements key elements of President Trump’s day-one executive order to unleash Alaska’s extraordinary resource potential—is great news for our state and, once again, proves that we have a partner in progress in this administration. As the incoming Trump administration was crafting the Alaska EO, @GovDunleavy and I worked directly with them to make sure these three vital provisions were included. Opening the ANWR Coastal Plain and the NPR-A to responsible resource development has been a longtime goal for Alaska's congressional delegation, Republican presidential administrations, and leaders in Alaska. Additionally, DOI’s order today lifts land withdrawals along the Dalton Highway Corridor, which contains the lifeblood of Alaska—the Trans-Alaska Pipeline—and allows those lands to be conveyed to the State of Alaska, securing this vital artery for future resource development, including access to the Ambler Mining District and the right-of-way for a future Alaska LNG pipeline. I want to thank President Trump and Secretary Burgum for fulfilling their commitment to unleash our state and help us realize a future of wealth, sustainable private sector economic growth, and good-paying jobs for our working families.

Many prisoners preferred Alcatraz due to its advanced security, including early metal detectors. The prison enforced strict rules, including near-total silence.

Name: Lynch, Stephen F.
text:
Congress established the U.S. Institute of Peace in 1984 via bipartisan legislation signed by President Ronald Reagan. 
 
As former Chairman of the Subcommittee on National Security, I have closely worked with the Institute and both Democratic and Republican Members of Congress to promote conflict resolution and international human rights in Afghanistan, Iraq, and other areas – in support of U.S. national security and global peace. Just last year, I participated in a USIP event that highlighted our bipartisan collaboration with Afghan female peace negotiators to protect and advance the rights of Afghan women and girls under Taliban rule.  
 
The removal of USIP leadership by President Trump and the DOGE takeover of this independent organization greatly undermine U.S. national security and contradicts a law duly enacted by Congress. As a member of the House Litigation Working Group, I will continue to support litigation initiated by the Institute to block these actions.

Name: Scholten, Hillary J.
text:
On this day in 1965, the Civil Rights March from Selma to Montgomery began, with around 3,200 brave marchers beginning the journey. Walking 12 miles a day and sleeping outside at night, their determination and bravery were key in shifting our nation’s history for the better.

I was honored to join @FaithandPolitic earlier this month on the anniversary of Bloody Sunday to honor the sacrifices made by Civil Rights Movement leaders, preachers, journalists, activists, and supporters. 

Our nation’s history cannot be erased, and it’s our duty to learn from these moments and keep them in our hearts and minds as we push toward a more just future for all.

Name: Friedman, Laura
text:
My new bipartisan bill – the Don’t Penalize Victims Act – makes sure charitable donations don’t disqualify victims from FEMA aid. It fixes outdated FEMA rules that considered donations a duplication of benefits.

It also clarifies the confusing legalese behind these rules. The last thing a family in disaster recovery should have to worry about is legal jargon.

Name: Friedman, Laura
text:
Victims shouldn’t have to worry about being taken advantage of either. My Stop Disaster Price Gouging Act protects families from people and businesses looking to make a quick buck.

It also prohibits price hikes on essential goods, housing and construction materials after a federally-declared disaster.

Any violators are hit with a $25,000 fine, the proceeds of which go right back to disaster victims. It would signal to price gougers that we have zero tolerance for their greed.

Name: Barr, Andy
text:
I want to address the handful of people who falsely claim they cannot reach anyone in my office or that I “refuse to hold town hall meetings.” Let me set the record straight.

Every day, my staff and I meet with constituents. Every day, we take phone calls, respond to emails and letters, and work diligently to resolve casework—regardless of political affiliation. We host monthly office hours in every county of the Sixth Congressional District as part of my ongoing accessibility initiative. We’ve done this consistently for 13 years, and I’m proud to lead one of the most accessible, professional, and responsive congressional staffs in the country.

What we will not do is provide a forum for individuals more interested in shouting and grandstanding than engaging in a respectful and constructive conversation. Our goal is to foster real dialogue—not theatrics.

That’s why we’re hosting a telephone town hall on Monday—to ensure a productive exchange of views in a civil environment where everyone has a chance to be heard.

Name: Bost, Mike
text: After my tour of Little Grassy Lake yesterday with U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, I was happy to sit down with local residents — hunters, anglers, and outdoor enthusiasts — at John A. Logan College to provide an update. So far, a third of the lake has been drained for repairs, and Fish and Wildlife is conducting a study to determine the full timeline for the project which they will share with us soon. Fish and Wildlife Services also confirmed a public meeting will be held in Carterville this summer to share more details with the community. Besides that, we also discussed preserving and expanding public access to our vast natural resources, including my legislation, the Shawnee TRAILS Act, which would allow year-round use of OHVs, ATVs, and e-bikes on designated trails in the forest. Thank you to all who attended for the great discussion.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories of remarkable individuals from across our district who are making a difference. This week, we shine a light on an incredible woman who is the embodiment of strength, compassion, and quiet heroism. Meet this week’s Hometown Hero: Diane Reitz of Levittown.
 
For over six decades, Diane Reitz has been a constant presence in our community—a devoted wife, mother, grandmother, and a servant leader in every sense. A nurse by profession and caregiver at heart, she’s led Girl Scout troops, championed wellness, and raised over $50,000 for women’s heart health. Through quiet acts of service, both seen and unseen, Diane has left a lasting mark on countless lives.
 
What makes Diane’s story extraordinary is not only the breadth of her service—but also the courage with which she continues it. Even now, in the face of unimaginable adversity, as she battles stage IV pancreatic cancer, she continues to serve with grace, humility, and purpose.
 
Of all her contributions, her work with our nation’s veterans speaks most powerfully to the depth of her character. In a world where invisible wounds often go unseen, Diane chose to see them—and to act. Together with Vietnam War hero Captain David A. Christian, she co-founded Victor Six Health and Fitness Organization, a groundbreaking program built on a simple but profound belief: restoring the body can help restore the mind.
 
What began as an idea rooted in compassion has become a lifeline for hundreds of veterans struggling with the weight of trauma. Through this program, veterans not only regain their physical strength but reconnect with hope, purpose, and life itself. The result is nothing short of extraordinary: since its founding, not one participant has taken their own life.
 
Diane’s impact transcends statistics. It lives in the veterans who now stand with renewed strength, in the families who have found healing and wholeness, and in the countless individuals who feel seen, heard, and uplifted because she chose to walk beside them. She has become a quiet force of hope in our community—a steadfast reminder of what it truly means to live a life of purpose, compassion, and unwavering service to others.
 
Thank you, Diane, for the example you’ve set and the lives you’ve touched and saved. Our community is better, kinder, and stronger because of you. You are, in every sense, a true Hometown Hero.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
I have co-sponsored every Article of Impeachment introduced in the House against unelected judges who believe they have the power to usurp Article II and override the authority of the duly elected President of the United States, chosen by a majority of the American people.

U.S. District Judge James Boasberg recently ordered that deportation flights carrying Venezuelan gang members—criminals responsible for the deaths of American citizens—be turned around mid-flight.

This ruling is not just an affront to the millions of Americans who support President Trump’s mission to secure our country, it is entirely nonjusticiable.

President Trump is our Commander-in-Chief and was exercising the powers fully vested in him by Article II of the Constitution. No judge at any level, including the Supreme Court, can limit the constitutional powers granted to the President.

Issuing such a weaponized, politically motivated judgment in bad faith undermines the credibility of our entire judicial system and demands immediate action from Article I to defend and uphold Article II.

Impeachment and removal from office is the constitutionally prescribed remedy, and it is urgently needed.

Unfortunately, Judge Boasberg is not alone. Other judges have similarly issued political rulings designed to undercut President Trump and his administration.

No single District Court judge in Washington, D.C., San Francisco, or anywhere else has more authority than the Presidency.

That’s why I’ve co-sponsored Articles of Impeachment against five federal judges so far. 

I’m also in support of legislative options to reign in rogue judges trying to play President. 

However, the easiest way to stop these rogue judges is for Congress to do our job and pass our own budget and policies through one big beautiful bill just like President Trump has asked us to. 

We are LAWMAKERS and we are the legislative body that can fund, defund, and make laws and then judges have to rule with the law.

No more CR’s.

No more kick the can down the road. 

Congress needs to take action and make President Trump’s agenda and executive orders the LAW.

Firing tens of thousands of VA employees while we have more veterans than ever relying on VA care will increase wait times and leave our vets without the care they need when they need it. We need more doctors and nurses at the VA, not less.
Read more for yourself.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Yesterday, I had the chance to visit the ROOTS Recovery Center, a facility I’m deeply proud to support. I secured $2,000,000 in federal funding for the City of Laredo Detoxification Center, now known as ROOTS, to ensure our community has access to the critical addiction treatment services we need. This funding supports staff salaries and essential resources, including electronic medical records, healthcare supplies, and food—resources that directly impact the care and well-being of those struggling with addiction.

During my tour, I had the opportunity to meet with patients and hear their personal stories. It was incredibly moving to witness their resilience and determination as they work toward recovery. ROOTS provides 24/7 medical detoxification services, crisis stabilization, and comprehensive support to help patients through their journey. It’s a place where people can find hope, healing, and the help they need to rebuild their lives. I’m truly committed to supporting ROOTS and the vital work they do every day to make a difference in people’s lives.

text:
This afternoon, I toured the Silver Creek Habitat Restoration Project in McHenry County—a truly beautiful stretch of natural land with enormous ecological potential.

The McHenry County Conservation District came to my office seeking support to restore ecological diversity in the wetlands and native prairies along the floodplain of Silver Creek, a main tributary of Nippersink Creek in north-central McHenry County. Their plan includes removing invasive brush and fallen trees, restoring stream banks, and replanting native species. I was proud to secure preliminary funding—$300,000—to help move this critical project forward.

Unfortunately, House Republicans are now holding it up.

This is exactly the kind of environmental project we should be supporting—restoring ecosystems, protecting our waterways, and preserving our natural heritage for future generations.

text:

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This week, I had the opportunity to join both the @LowerBksChamber & Central Bucks Chamber of Commerce for my annual State of the Union addresses—two great events centered around thoughtful conversations with the people powering our PA-1 economy.

In both meetings, I heard directly from community members, business owners, entrepreneurs, community leaders, and advocates about the issues that matter most—what’s working, where the roadblocks are, and how we can better support Bucks County from the federal level. The dialogue was insightful, the questions were sharp, and the commitment to our community was clear in every conversation.

A sincere thank you to all the attendees, LBCC Executive Director William Ferrara, CBCC President Theresa Fera, and all the chamber staff and organizers who brought these gatherings to life.The strength of our country starts at the local level—with those who invest in their neighborhoods, create jobs, and believe in the future of their communities. That spirit is alive and well in Bucks County! 

I look forward to continuing working together in our shared mission of empowering our local businesses, growing our economy, and delivering results for the people of Bucks County.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, we celebrate a national treasure, my dear friend, Mae Krier, as she turns 99 years young! Mae is a living legend whose strength, spirit, and service have not only shaped the course of history but inspired generations of Americans to believe in the power of patriotism and purpose.

Mae, of Levittown, is one of the original Rosie the Riveters who helped lead our nation to victory in WWII, but her service didn’t end there. For decades, she’s championed recognition for her fellow Rosies, and I’ve been proud to work alongside her in this fight. Leading the Rosie the Riveter Congressional Gold Medal Act was one of the greatest honors of my career, and presenting Mae with the medal on the shores of Normandy, on the 80th anniversary of D-Day, was a moment I’ll never forget.

And now, on this milestone birthday, I am proud to introduce the Rosie the Riveter Day Act — legislation that will formally recognize March 21st each year as a day to honor the courage, sacrifice, and legacy of Mae and her fellow Rosies. 

Happy Birthday, Mae, my dear friend! You are a hero, a fighter, and an icon. Your life is a living reminder that patriotism is not just a word — it’s a lifetime of service, persistence, and heart. You’ve shown us that it’s never too late to fight for what’s right and that one voice, can move mountains. Here’s to 99 incredible years!

The Commonwealth of Massachusetts receives over $2 billion in annual funding from the Department of Education to help support nearly one million students enrolled in about 1,800 K-12 local schools and other institutions and programs across the state.

Name: Khanna, Ro
text: 866 people lost their jobs this week when 5 factories closed and 4 conducted mass layoffs.

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
Many rural U.S. communities rely on good-paying factory jobs, but as deindustrialization has taken hold, these jobs have been slowly eliminated.  

Congress can restore industry to these towns. Here are what factories closed this week, why, and what we can do to help:

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
In Muskegon, Michigan, spring manufacturer Michigan Spring & Stamping of Muskegon closed and fired 116 people after being sold to German manufacturer Kern-Liebers.

https://t.co/sxigAxVOOL

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
Columbus Manufacturing, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Hormel Foods Corporation, in Hayward, California closed after 100 years in operation and laid off 125 employees.

https://t.co/AMUUdzGkUq

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
In Shreveport, Louisiana, 107 workers were laid off when Indian pharmaceutical manufacturer Dr. Reddy’s Laboratories downsized.

https://t.co/1lr0nXDIF1

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
Plastics manufacturer ORBIS Corporation in Menasha, Wisconsin fired 109 workers after downsizing to a facility in Texas.

https://t.co/zO2TrWjG3A

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
In Jeffersonville, Indiana, mattress and bedding manufacturer Resident Home, closed and fired 106 employees after being acquired by Ashley Furniture for $2 billion last March.

https://t.co/5yMMuusdfW

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
Glass manufacturer, Press Glass, Inc., in Stoneville, North Carolina closed leaving 68 people without jobs.

The company consolidated operations to its recent $155.2 million expansion of its facility in Ridgeway, Virginia.

https://t.co/3rbaSkJMPe

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
86 people were permanently laid off from Japanese automotive and aerospace manufacturer, Nitto Inc., in Chesapeake, Virginia after announcing a new multimillion-dollar facility in Frankfort, Kentucky.

This is a prime example of how Congress can attract and rebuild manufacturing towns using federal investments.

https://t.co/zaNCLkXrjd.

Name: Khanna, Ro
text:
In San Jose, Japanese semiconductor manufacturer Renesas Electronics Corporation, laid off 3 more workers after cutting 63 from other facilities.

Investments such as the CHIPS Act, which I co-authored, and offshoring penalties will help keep semiconductor manufacturing jobs in the U.S. by increasing private sector investments.

https://t.co/UVys5mcMR3

https://t.co/HVxIaGl3j5

Name: Barrett, Tom
text: Since taking office two months ago, I’ve traveled to every county in my district multiple times in a sincere effort to meet with constituents from all walks of life. I’ve visited small businesses, schools, hospitals, non-profits, military units, veterans groups, and local governments. Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
TX-02 lost a legend.
 
George Foreman wasn’t just a champion in the ring—he was a champion for our community.

Raised in Houston’s 5th Ward, he knew struggle. He turned that struggle into strength—winning Olympic gold in 1968, becoming a two-time heavyweight champion of the world, and redefining what redemption looks like. 

After walking away from boxing, George found faith. He became an ordained minister, started the George Foreman Youth and Community Center right here in Houston, and spent decades mentoring at-risk kids. 

He named all five of his sons George Edward Foreman. Why? To create unity. To build a bond that said, “If one goes up, we all go up.”

George gave his time, his resources, and his heart—quietly and consistently. From Kingwood to Huffman, folks knew “Big George” as the man who showed up, supported local schools, bought class projects just to give them back, and donated signed gloves to every charity that asked.

He never stopped serving. He never stopped believing. And he never forgot where he came from.

Rest in peace.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Last night, we came together to celebrate the newest class of Victor Six graduates—a group of heroic veterans from our community who just completed a powerful 12-week program built on a life-changing belief: restoring the body can help restore the mind. This program is making a real and lasting difference—giving our veterans the tools, support, and sense of purpose they need and deserve as they move forward in their journey.

What made the night even more special was the chance to honor the incredible Diane Reitz, who founded Victor Six alongside Vietnam War hero David Christian. Diane is the heart and soul of this mission. Even as she bravely battles Stage IV pancreatic cancer, her unwavering dedication to our veterans has created a place where lives aren’t just changed—they’re saved.

It was my profound honor to present her with a Congressional Record as a lasting tribute to her extraordinary impact. Please join me in applauding Diane and congratulating all of our inspiring Victor Six graduates!

Name: King-Hinds, Kimberlyn
text:
Today, we celebrate Covenant Day, a moment to reflect on the vision, foresight, and persistence of our founders, the meaning of choosing to be Americans, and the progress we’ve made since joining the American political family.

But the Covenant is more than just a historic document—it’s a living commitment.

To me, it’s both an ideal and a tool, one that survives through our actions and advocacy. It reminds us that our unique identity within the United States must be continually protected and uplifted.

As we mark 49 years since the signing, it’s up to us to give life to this agreement, to defend our rights, and to stay true to the principles of self-government and self-determination—even when it’s hard.

Here’s to honoring the past, meeting the moment, and continuing to define our future.

Happy Covenant Day, CNMI!

#cnmi

This legislation, introduced by Congressman Chris Smith (NJ-04), aims to hold the CCP accountable for its actions. We will not allow them to get away with stealing American jobs and intellectual property, all while committing human rights abuses against their own citizens. We are committed to protecting American interests and upholding human rights standards globally.

I’ve long said you must be skeptical of “influencers” on this platform. They’re paid by campaigns, companies, Super PACS, and they don't care whether the mission is liberal or conservative.

I’m old enough to remember when conservatives believed SNAP and other programs should be transitory safety nets, not government funded junk and luxury food.

So why would so-called conservatives suddenly be okay with no limitations on what SNAP recipients can buy?

Not because they’re independent thinkers — they’re shilling for the soda industry. Same playbook, different day: flood social media with fake outrage and hope you don’t notice the money behind it.

Many “conservatives” did the same thing to defend PBM’s from being reformed in the CR last December too. Yeah they were paid by the BIGGEST of Big Pharma.

text:
To review some basic conservative ideology: Taxpayer-funded programs like SNAP shouldn’t be used to buy soda and junk food. Period.

Some people are pushing back with, “Shouldn’t conservatives believe people can buy whatever they want?” Sure — with their own money. But when it’s taxpayer dollars? That’s different. We have a responsibility to ensure that government programs don’t subsidize long-term health problems — which we *also* end up paying for.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1958, Elvis Presley was inducted into the U.S. Army. 

It was widely covered by the media, with his manager, Colonel Tom Parker, ensuring that every moment was documented, including when Elvis received his famous G.I. haircut. Although Elvis was offered the opportunity to entertain the troops and have better housing by enlisting in Special Services, he chose to serve as a regular soldier.

Elvis served in Germany for 18 months, where he met his future wife, Priscilla. He was honorably discharged from the Army in 1960.

Name: Harris, Andy
text:
When the Farm Bill was debated in 2013, the soda industry pulled all the stops to maintain billions of government dollars going to sugary drinks in the SNAP program. 

In recent years, soda companies funneled money to dozens of public health groups to confuse the impacts of sugary drinks on health. 

Let’s be clear, we are not calling for unhealthy foods to be banned by the federal government.

But funneling billions of taxpayer dollars to subsidize unhealthy food or beverages for children, and, in turn, increasing the risk of diabetes, is not an example of the freedom we all hold dear, or a responsible use of taxpayer dollars. 

Instead, this is an example of a rigged market, government cronyism, and a dereliction of our duty to children.

text: On this day in 1825, the Mexican legislature, meeting in Saltillo, passed the State Colonization Law of March 24, 1825. The legislation was designed to bring about the peopling of Coahuila and Texas.  @TxStHistAssoc

Name: Cornyn, John
text: It encouraged farming, ranching, and commerce. For a nominal fee, the law granted settlers as much as a square league (4,428.4 acres) of pastureland and a labor (177.1 acres) of farmland. Immigrants were temporarily free of every kind of tax. Newcomers had to take an oath promising to abide by the federal and state constitutions, to worship according to the Christian (i.e., Catholic) religion, and to display sound moral principles and good conduct.

Name: Cornyn, John

I spent Thursday on base, taking a deep dive with Garrison Commander Colonel Gore and her team discussing readiness and touring important quality of life issues like on-base housing and childcare. As a Member of the House Armed Services Committee, it was an honor to witness the mission firsthand and sit down with service members from the Army, Navy, Marines, and Space Force for a candid lunch. 
 
We then met with the @FtMeadeAlliance to discuss the broader community and incredible business support for Fort Meade. This was the start of our Maryland military installation tour—more to come!

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Yesterday in San Antonio, I stood with the National Association of Letter Carriers (NALC) and letter carriers from across the country as they said HELL NO to dismantling the U.S. Postal Service.

It was an honor to stand alongside Homer Hernandez, President of the NALC Alamo Branch, and other letter carriers as we showed our strong solidarity in protecting postal workers and defending this vital public service. I joined fellow Congressional representatives in voicing our firm opposition to any efforts that would threaten the future of the U.S. Postal Service—an institution protected by the Constitution of the United States.

The NALC raised important concerns about the potential privatization or dismantling of the Postal Service, and I stand with them in ensuring that doesn’t happen. The Postal Service is a lifeline for communities across this nation, and we must continue to support it, safeguard it, and ensure it remains a public service for the people. I am fully committed to standing with our postal workers and protecting the U.S. Postal Service for future generations!

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
We have the best shot we’ve had in years to dismantle the Mexican drug cartels. We’ve got willing partners in Mexico, and we’ve got President Trump. To get it done, Congress needs to act, and that has been surprisingly difficult considering how popular this issue is.

I’m pushing @SpeakerJohnson hard to establish a Select Committee to Defeat the Mexican Drug Cartels. This is something nearly every Committee Chair supports and co-sponsored. What exactly does that look like? It means real resources. Professional staff. And a focused mission to confront this threat head-on.

For the last two years, I’ve been leading a task force without staff, without funding — over 30 meetings with experts and officials, multiple trips to Mexico, Colombia, and Panama. We’ve laid the groundwork. Now it’s time to scale it.

This issue cuts across ten different committees. That means no one owns it — and that’s a recipe for inaction. A Select Committee would fix that. It would focus Congress, align with the administration, and help deliver effective solutions.

The cartels are our greatest narco-terror threat. The mission is clear. The moment is now. We should vote on this Select Committee next week and get to work.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:

- California raised minimum wages aggressively
- Let trial lawyers weaponize labor laws
- Has one of the most punishing tax codes in America
- Regulatory red tape that drives up costs for everyone

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Texas, meanwhile, kept taxes low, kept regulations in check, and created an environment where job creators, especially small businesses, could actually build, hire, and grow. This wasn’t luck. It was intentional—and it’s working.

Economic policy isn’t abstract. It shows up in your paycheck, your cost of living, and whether or not your town has opportunity.

California and Texas are running two very different experiments. We’re watching the results in real time.

SSA hearing rooms will still be available nearby, and the main office serving this region at 1715 W NASA Blvd, Melbourne, remains fully operational just 11 minutes away. The closure of this hearing space will not affect anyone’s benefits, nor does it reduce services.

Name: Cornyn, John
text:
Grok: There are numerous ways to prepare brisket, depending on culinary traditions, equipment, and personal preferences. Here are some of the most popular methods:

1. **Smoking**: A classic method, especially in Texas-style barbecue. Brisket is seasoned with a simple rub (usually salt and pepper) and slow-cooked over indirect heat from wood (like oak, hickory, or mesquite) for 10-14 hours at a low temperature (225-250°F). This creates a tender brisket with a smoky flavor and a signature "bark" on the outside.

2. **Braising**: Common in Jewish cuisine, brisket is seared, then slow-cooked in a covered pot with liquid (e.g., beef broth, wine, or tomato sauce) and aromatics like onions, garlic, and carrots. It’s cooked at 300-325°F for 3-4 hours until fork-tender, often served with the resulting gravy.

3. **Oven Roasting**: Similar to braising but with less liquid, this method involves seasoning the brisket, placing it in a roasting pan, and cooking it low and slow (around 275-300°F) for 4-6 hours. It can be uncovered for a crusty exterior or covered for a softer texture.

4. **Slow Cooker/Crockpot**: A convenient option where the brisket is seasoned, placed in the slow cooker with some liquid (broth, BBQ sauce, or beer), and cooked on low for 8-10 hours or high for 4-6 hours. It’s low-effort and yields a juicy result.

5. **Grilling**: Less common but viable for smaller cuts. The brisket is seasoned and cooked over indirect heat on a grill, often wrapped in foil or butcher paper partway through to retain moisture, taking 6-8 hours at low heat.

6. **Pressure Cooker/Instant Pot**: For a faster option, brisket is seared, then cooked under high pressure with liquid (e.g., broth or BBQ sauce) for about 60-90 minutes, followed by a natural pressure release. It’s tender but lacks the smoky or roasted flavor of slower methods.

7. **Sous Vide**: A modern technique where the seasoned brisket is vacuum-sealed and cooked in a water bath at a precise temperature (typically 155-165°F) for 24-36 hours. It’s then finished with a quick sear or broil for texture. This ensures consistent tenderness.

8. **Corned Beef**: Brisket is cured in a saltwater brine with spices (like peppercorns, coriander, and bay leaves) for several days, then simmered slowly for 3-4 hours. Popular in Irish-American dishes like corned beef and cabbage.

9. **Pastrami**: A variation of corned beef, where the cured brisket is coated with a spice rub (heavy on black pepper and coriander), smoked, and steamed. This is a staple in delis, especially for sandwiches.

10. **Boiling/Simmering**: A basic method where brisket is submerged in seasoned water or broth and simmered for 3-4 hours. It’s simple but less flavorful unless paired with a robust sauce or seasoning.

Beyond these, preparation can vary by:
- **Seasoning**: Dry rubs (e.g., paprika, garlic powder, cayenne), marinades, or just salt and pepper.
- **Cooking Time**: From quick pressure cooking to multi-day curing and smoking.
- **Cultural Twists**: Like Korean-inspired brisket with soy sauce and ginger, or Mexican-style with chili and lime.

In practice, there are dozens of combinations—smoked then braised, oven-roasted with a BBQ glaze, etc.—so the exact number depends on how finely you split the differences. Which method are you most curious about?

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
I've worked at the White House for both Democrat and Republican Presidents and I've never seen this kind of mishandling of classified info. It's sloppy at best and puts the military involved in these sensitive operations at risk.

Let me explain why. 🧵https://t.co/NFTVbIINO7

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
They shared details on specific targets U.S. troops would try to hit, and what specific weapons they would be using.

That’s a problem even before they accidentally looped in a journalist.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Our most senior government officials -- including the Vice President, Secretary of Defense, CIA Director, and National Security Advisor -- planned a military strike via group chat on Signal, an unclassified texting app.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Laws like the Espionage Act, the Presidential Records Act, and the Federal Records Act lay out clear rules for how you can handle classified information — and those laws apply to every one of the people on that text chain.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: We also know that China, Russia, and Iran are constantly trying to hack the phones of everyone in that group chat. This is why we have a whole separate computer network to handle classified information.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: For years, I locked up my phone every day b/c it wasn't safe to bring it into an office where we handled and talked about classified docs. Everyone who does classified work knows this. So do the people on this group chat, many of whom have railed against breaches of security.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: This is all classified information. Even the fact that they were considering this strike is classified. And for good reason: the time and method of an attack, if intercepted by our enemies, could have gotten American troops killed.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
If these were regular soldiers or a civilian CIA officer like I was, they would be reprimanded, likely fired, prosecuted and possibly jailed. 

But this Administration believes they are above the law — and seemingly don’t care what US forces and US operations they put at risk.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: If the DOJ decided to prosecute, the individual would be immediately terminated and arrested, and potentially face fines up to $250,000, imprisonment for up to 10 years, or both.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: They would also likely be reported to the Department of Justice in a “crimes report” for further investigation and potential prosecution, and be reported to Congress if the disclosure caused significant harm or damage to national security.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: The agency Inspector General would then likely investigate to determine whether additional action is warranted. Such action could include a written reprimand, loss of their security clearance, termination, and even loss of retirement pay.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Depending on the outcome, the individual could be flagged as a threat in the security clearance databases shared across the intelligence and defense communities, significantly impacting their ability to get future work in the government and with national security contractors.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Right now, one unelected judge can shut down an entire national policy—immigration enforcement, border security, you name it. They’re using that power to block deportations and stall President Trump’s agenda before it even gets off the ground.

I don’t believe the judicial check was ever meant to be used so prolifically. It’s a necessary check, no doubt. There will often be disagreement between the Executive (charged to “execute” the law), and the courts. This is usually the fault of Congress for writing laws that are vague in nature. But that “check” cannot be a single unelected judge, effectively empowered with the same “execution” authority as the President. We must properly balance this important mechanism of checks and balances. 

That’s why I support the No Rogue Rulings Act. This bill reins in activist judges by stopping them from issuing broad, nationwide rulings in cases that should only apply to the people directly involved. It restores balance between the courts, Congress, and the executive branch—just like the Constitution intended.
